.TH "LESS" "1" "2026\-04\-12" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
less \- terminal pager with ANSI colour passthrough, search, and follow
mode
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]less\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]+command\f[R]] [\f[I]file\f[R]
\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Displays file content (or stdin) one screen at a time.
When no file is given, reads from stdin.
At most one file argument is currently accepted; for concatenated paging
of multiple files, use \f[B]cat file1 file2 | less\f[R].
Multi\-file paging with \f[B]:n\f[R] / \f[B]:p\f[R] navigation is
tracked for a future release.
.PP
ANSI escape codes are passed through unchanged by default, so coloured
output from tools like \f[B]man\f[R], \f[B]files\f[R], and
\f[B]treex\f[R] renders correctly.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-N\f[R]
Show line numbers.
.TP
\f[B]\-S\f[R]
Chop long lines instead of wrapping.
.TP
\f[B]\-F\f[R]
Quit immediately if all content fits on one screen.
.TP
\f[B]\-R\f[R]
Pass raw ANSI colour codes through unchanged (on by default unless
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R] is set).
.TP
\f[B]\-X\f[R]
Do not clear the screen on exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-i\f[R]
Case\-insensitive search, ignored when the pattern contains an uppercase
letter.
.TP
\f[B]\-I\f[R]
Case\-insensitive search always, regardless of pattern case.
.TP
\f[B]+F\f[R]
Start in follow mode, like \f[B]tail \-f\f[R].
Press \f[B]q\f[R] to exit follow mode.
.TP
\f[B]+G\f[R]
Jump to end of file on open.
.TP
\f[B]+/\f[R]_pattern_
Start with an initial forward search for \f[I]pattern\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R][=\f[I]WHEN\f[R]]
Coloured output: auto (default when omitted), always, or never.
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable ANSI colour passthrough; raw escape sequences are displayed as
text.
.TP
\f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version and exit.
.SH KEY BINDINGS
.TP
\f[B]q\f[R]
Quit.
.TP
\f[B]j\f[R] / Down arrow
Scroll down one line.
.TP
\f[B]k\f[R] / Up arrow
Scroll up one line.
.TP
Space / PgDn
Scroll down one screen.
.TP
PgUp
Scroll up one screen.
.TP
Home / \f[B]g\f[R]
Jump to beginning.
.TP
End / \f[B]G\f[R]
Jump to end.
.TP
\f[B]/\f[R]
Forward search.
.TP
\f[B]?\f[R]
Backward search.
.TP
\f[B]n\f[R]
Next search match.
.TP
\f[B]N\f[R]
Previous search match.
.TP
\f[B]F\f[R]
Enter follow mode (press \f[B]q\f[R] to exit).
.TP
\f[B]\-N\f[R]
Toggle line numbers.
.TP
\f[B]\-S\f[R]
Toggle line chopping.
.SH WILDCARDS
On Windows, cmd.exe and PowerShell do not expand \f[B]*\f[R] and
\f[B]?\f[R] wildcards before starting programs, so \f[B]less\f[R]
expands them itself.
\f[B]less *.log\f[R] works the same as in bash.
\f[B][\&...]\f[R] is matched literally (brackets are legal Windows
filename characters).
\f[B]**\f[R] is rejected with a usage error \(em \f[B]less\f[R] has no
recursive mode; use \f[B]files\f[R] to find files recursively.
A pattern that matches nothing is passed through unchanged so the normal
\(lqnot found\(rq error follows.
In cmd, quoting a pattern (e.g.\ \f[I]\(lq*.log\(rq\f[R]) suppresses
expansion.
Note \f[B]less\f[R] accepts a single file, so a pattern must resolve to
exactly one match \(em two or more matches exit 2 with a usage error
(the same thing happens in bash when the shell expands).
On Linux and macOS the shell expands wildcards as usual and
\f[B]less\f[R] does nothing extra.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Normal exit.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Error (file not found, read error).
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Usage error (bad arguments).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]LESS\f[R]
Controls default options.
Three states distinguished: when \f[B]unset\f[R], Winix \f[B]less\f[R]
uses modern defaults \f[B]FRX\f[R] (quit\-if\-one\-screen, raw colour,
no\-init); when \f[B]set to a non\-empty value\f[R], replaces the
defaults entirely (parsed as list of options, unknown flags ignored);
when \f[B]set to an empty string\f[R] (\f[B]LESS=\f[R]), disables all
defaults so every option must come from CLI flags.
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables ANSI colour passthrough (no\-color.org).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
less somefile.txt

man timeit | less

less \-N somefile.txt

less \-S somefile.txt

less +F logfile.log

less +G somefile.txt

less +/error logfile.log

less \-F somefile.txt
.EE
